    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nationalism is a double-edged sword in sociology, often serving as a necessary glue for social cohesion while simultaneously posing significant risks when it becomes exclusionary or authoritarian. On one hand, it fosters a strong sense of shared identity and collective action that can stabilize societies during times of crisis or rapid change. On the other hand, when nationalism overrides universal human rights and marginalizes minority groups, it has historically led to conflict, discrimination, and the erosion of democratic values. Ultimately, the danger lies not in the concept itself, but in how rigidly it is enforced and whether it prioritizes the \"other\" over the \"self.\"",
      "source": "target",
